In Linux, the `net.ipv4.tcp_rmem` sysctl setting defines the minimum, default, and maximum buffer sizes for TCP socket receive buffers. Unfortunately, you can't directly retrieve the third parameter (which corresponds to the maximum buffer size) of `net.ipv4.tcp_rmem` via `getsockopt()` because this is a system-wide setting and is not exposed on a per-socket basis through the socket options API.

However, you can retrieve the current buffer size set on a specific socket by using `getsockopt()` with the `SO_RCVBUF` option. This gives you the current receive buffer size for that socket, which is influenced by `net.ipv4.tcp_rmem` but possibly adjusted by the kernel's auto-tuning mechanism or any calls you made to `setsockopt()` with `SO_RCVBUF`.

Here is a quick example in C on how to retrieve the receive buffer size for a given TCP socket:

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <unistd.h>
#include <sys/socket.h>

int main() {
    int sock, res;
    int recvBufSize;
    socklen_t optSize;

    // Create a TCP socket
    sock = socket(AF_INET, SOCK_STREAM, 0);
    if (sock == -1) {
        perror("socket");
        return EXIT_FAILURE;
    }

    // Retrieve receive buffer size
    optSize = sizeof(recvBufSize);
    res = getsockopt(sock, SOL_SOCKET, SO_RCVBUF, &recvBufSize, &optSize);
    if (res == -1) {
        perror("getsockopt");
        close(sock);
        return EXIT_FAILURE;
    }

    // Output the receive buffer size
    printf("TCP receive buffer size: %d\n", recvBufSize);

    // Close the socket
    close(sock);

    return EXIT_SUCCESS;
}
```

If you want to retrieve the system-wide `net.ipv4.tcp_rmem` settings themselves, you can do this by reading the `/proc/sys/net/ipv4/tcp_rmem` file or using the `sysctl` command in the shell:

```sh
cat /proc/sys/net/ipv4/tcp_rmem
# or
sysctl net.ipv4.tcp_rmem
```

This will output the minimum, default, and maximum receive buffer sizes. To get the same information in an application, you could read and parse the contents of `/proc/sys/net/ipv4/tcp_rmem` file.

Keep in mind that direct manipulation and reading of sysctl settings typically require root privileges, so accessing `/proc/sys/net/ipv4/tcp_rmem` programmatically will also require appropriate permissions.

The `net.core.rmem_max` is a sysctl setting in Linux that specifies the maximum receive socket buffer size that can be set by applications for all protocols. In other words, it's the globally allowed maximum for the SO_RCVBUF option when you're adjusting socket receive buffer sizes via `setsockopt()`.

You cannot directly retrieve `net.core.rmem_max` via `getsockopt()` since it is a system-wide limit and not a per-socket option. The `getsockopt()` function will only return the current receive buffer size that's set for a specific socket, not the global maximum.

However, you can check the `rmem_max` value by reading the `/proc/sys/net/core/rmem_max` file or by using the `sysctl` command in the shell:

```sh
cat /proc/sys/net/core/rmem_max
# or
sysctl net.core.rmem_max
```

To access `net.core.rmem_max` programmatically from within an application, you would need to open and read the `/proc/sys/net/core/rmem_max` file, like so:

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <fcntl.h>
#include <unistd.h>

int main() {
    int fd, ret;
    char buffer[64];

    fd = open("/proc/sys/net/core/rmem_max", O_RDONLY);
    if (fd < 0) {
        perror("open");
        return EXIT_FAILURE;
    }

    ret = read(fd, buffer, sizeof(buffer) - 1);
    if (ret < 0) {
        perror("read");
        close(fd);
        return EXIT_FAILURE;
    }

    buffer[ret] = '\0';  // null-terminate the string
    printf("net.core.rmem_max = %s\n", buffer);

    close(fd);
    return EXIT_SUCCESS;
}
```

Remember that reading `rmem_max` is typically a non-privileged action, but modifying the value `/proc/sys/net/core/rmem_max` or using `sysctl` to set the value would require root privileges. Therefore, trying to set a buffer size larger than the current `rmem_max` value by using `setsockopt()` and `SO_RCVBUF` would be unsuccessful unless you've previously increased `rmem_max` as a privileged user.

To programmatically get the maximum socket buffer size on macOS or DragonFly BSD, you would typically use a system call to read the `sysctl` settings. Here is a C language example that demonstrates how to do this using the `sysctlbyname()` function which is available on both systems:

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <sys/types.h>
#include <sys/sysctl.h>

int main() {
    int maxsockbuf;
    size_t len = sizeof(maxsockbuf);

    // For macOS, this might be kern.ipc.maxsockbuf or net.inet.tcp.recvspace, etc.
    // For DragonFly BSD, you may need to use a different MIB name based on the available documentation.
    // Here I've shown the line for macOS' maximum socket buffer:
    if (sysctlbyname("kern.ipc.maxsockbuf", &maxsockbuf, &len, NULL, 0) == -1) {
        perror("sysctlbyname");
        return EXIT_FAILURE;
    }

    printf("Maximum socket buffer size: %d\n", maxsockbuf);

    return EXIT_SUCCESS;
}
```

In this code snippet, `sysctlbyname()` reads the value of a sysctl setting given its name. Here's what you need to replace `"kern.ipc.maxsockbuf"` with, depending on what you're looking for:

- For macOS, you might check `kern.ipc.maxsockbuf`, `net.inet.tcp.recvspace`, and `net.inet.tcp.sendspace`.
- For DragonFly BSD, based on the sysctl MIBs you want to inspect, you would use the appropriate names such as `net.socket.recvbuf_max_size` and `net.socket.sendbuf_max_size`.

You need to compile and run this code on the system you're interested in, and you might have to consult the system documentation for the correct sysctl variable names specific to that system.

Remember that the availability of sysctl settings can vary between different UNIX-like systems and versions, so you should consult the system's documentation or use `sysctl -a` on the command line to explore the available sysctl settings to query programmatically.

There isn't a completely universal way to get system settings like maximum socket buffer sizes across all BSD variants because each BSD operating system can have its own sysctl MIB (Management Information Base) scheme. However, `sysctl` is a common tool present in all BSD systems and in macOS for querying system settings.

If you are developing a program intended to run on multiple BSD variants, you can structure your code to handle different cases based on the specific operating systems, perhaps checking for system-specific identifiers and then querying the appropriate sysctl settings.

Here's an example of how you might approach this in C:

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <sys/types.h>
#include <sys/sysctl.h>
#include <string.h>

int main() {
    int maxsockbuf;
    size_t len = sizeof(maxsockbuf);
    int result;

#if defined(__FreeBSD__)
    // FreeBSD sysctl MIB for maximum socket buffer size
    result = sysctlbyname("kern.ipc.maxsockbuf", &maxsockbuf, &len, NULL, 0);
#elif defined(__NetBSD__) || defined(__OpenBSD__) || defined(__DragonFly__)
    // NetBSD, OpenBSD, and DragonFly BSD sysctl MIB for maximum socket buffer size
    result = sysctlbyname("kern.sbmax", &maxsockbuf, &len, NULL, 0);
#elif defined(__APPLE__) && defined(__MACH__)
    // macOS sysctl MIB for maximum socket buffer size
    result = sysctlbyname("kern.ipc.maxsockbuf", &maxsockbuf, &len, NULL, 0);
#else
    #error "Unsupported BSD variant"
#endif

    if (result == -1) {
        perror("sysctlbyname");
        return EXIT_FAILURE;
    }

    printf("Maximum socket buffer size: %d\n", maxsockbuf);

    return EXIT_SUCCESS;
}
```

In this example, you'd use macro checks to determine which variant of BSD or macOS you're compiling on, and then call the appropriate sysctl MIB. This way, your code has branches to handle different cases, although the overall structure is kept as universal as possible.

This requires you to be aware of the differences between the systems, and you must maintain the code as system variations evolve over time. It is always recommended to check the documentation of the target operating system to ensure that the correct sysctl MIBs are being used.
